          "body": "The chapter's central word is *hupokrites* — Greek theater vocabulary for an actor wearing a mask. Six of the seven (or seven of the eight) woes name it directly. Hypocrisy in Matthew 23 is not occasional moral failure; it is a stable structure of religious identity in which the public performance and the private reality are systematically misaligned. The Pharisees are not failing to live up to their teaching — they are *performing* their teaching for audience effect (v. 5) while inwardly being something else (vv. 25-28). This is why Jesus reserves His severest language for them and not for the openly irreligious. Tax collectors and prostitutes (21:31) are at least not deceived about themselves. The hypocrite has constructed a self that even he cannot see past, which is why the woes pile up the metaphors of blindness — *blind guides* (vv. 16, 24), *blind men* (vv. 17, 19), *blind Pharisee* (v. 26). The disease is uncurable from inside the system."
