          "body": "Verses 37-39 are theologically essential to the chapter. Without them, Matthew 23 reads as raw prosecutorial fury. *With* them, the chapter is revealed as judgment delivered in grief. *Jerusalem, Jerusalem* — the doubled name is the OT pattern of mourning address (Genesis 22:11; Exodus 3:4; 1 Samuel 3:10). Jesus' image — a mother hen gathering chicks under her wings — draws on Deuteronomy 32:11 (the eagle hovering over its young) and Psalm 91:4 (refuge under His wings), claiming for Himself the protective role YHWH assumed for Israel. The verb *episunago* (gather together) is His own kingdom-gathering vocabulary (24:31). The tragedy is concentrated in three words: *kai ouk ethelesate* — *and you were unwilling*. The same Christ who pronounces seven woes weeps over the city the woes have judged. The verdict in v. 38 (*your house is being left to you desolate*) is not vindictive; it ratifies what the unwilling have chosen. Verse 39 leaves a door open: *until you say, Blessed is He who comes in the name of the Lord* — Psalm 118:26, the same psalm shouted at the triumphal entry (21:9). The judgment has an expiration date; the King will return when the city receives Him."
